question.title: Tomcat webapp error - application started thread [AWT-Windows] but has failed to stop it - memory leak?

node.contents: I didn't notice it until today during some testing locally on my pc, that Tomcat had posted an error in the log file. I'm using Tomcat 6.0.29 and Java JDK 1.6.

astNode.text: I didn't notice it until today during some testing locally on my pc, that Tomcat had posted an error in the log file. I'm using Tomcat 6.0.29 and Java JDK 1.6.

node.contents: Dec 1, 2010 12:36:57 pm org.apache.catalina.core.StandardContext reload INFO: Reloading this Context has started Dec 1, 2010 12:36:57 pm org.apache.catalina.loader.WebappClassLoader clearReferencesThreads SEVER: The web application [/AutoSpyder] appears to have started a thread named [AWT-Windows] but has failed to stop it. This is very likely to create a memory leak.

astNode.text: Dec 1, 2010 12:36:57 pm org.apache.catalina.core.StandardContext reload INFO: Reloading this Context has started Dec 1, 2010 12:36:57 pm org.apache.catalina.loader.WebappClassLoader clearReferencesThreads SEVER: The web application [/AutoSpyder] appears to have started a thread named [AWT-Windows] but has failed to stop it. This is very likely to create a memory leak.

node.contents: What? I've never seen this before. So I checked my log file from yesterday, and sure enough, this error was there too. I don't quite understand what's causing this.

astNode.text: What? I've never seen this before. So I checked my log file from yesterday, and sure enough, this error was there too. I don't quite understand what's causing this.

node.contents: Can I assume that it would have to be one of my servlets that uses objects from the java.awt package? If so, how do I pinpoint the code that is causing this?

node.contents: Your thread dump does look clean, and if you are not experienceing any major memory issues, I would assume your application will be fine. The message you found in your logs is INFO, so it is not an Error or Fatal exception. If you haven't done it already, use an application such as JMeter to load test your application and using VisualVM, you can profile what will be happening to your application under real load. Also in Tomcat, make sure to set the -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError flag. This way if you do run into memory problems, you will have a good starting ground for your analysis
